#compdef caire
# =============================================================================
# caire — Endre Simo's "Content aware image resize library"
#         — a Go CLI for SEAM CARVING: resizing images while
#         preserving important content by finding and removing
#         (or duplicating) "low-energy" seams (vertical /
#         horizontal pixel paths with minimal visual
#         importance).  Implements the Avidan-Shamir 2007
#         seam-carving algorithm with face-detection
#         protection (pigo) to avoid distorting human faces.
#         Distinguishing from ImageMagick (-resize), GIMP's
#         content-aware scaling, and other image resizers by:
#           - SEAM CARVING — Avidan-Shamir 2007 algorithm:
#             1. Compute pixel-energy map (gradient magnitude
#                via Sobel filter)
#             2. Find lowest-energy seam (continuous path of
#                pixels from top to bottom OR left to right)
#             3. Remove (shrink) or duplicate (enlarge) the
#                seam
#             4. Repeat until target dimensions reached
#           - SOBEL EDGE DETECTION via gradient computation —
#             pixels in high-gradient regions (edges, faces,
#             objects) get high energy + protected from seam
#             selection; low-gradient regions (smooth
#             backgrounds, sky) get removed first
#           - GAUSSIAN BLUR PREPROCESSING via --blur N — blur
#             the energy map to smooth out noise; default
#             radius 4
#           - SOBEL THRESHOLD via --sobel N — gradient magnitude
#             below this threshold is treated as zero energy
#             (more aggressive carving); default 2
#           - FACE DETECTION via --face flag — uses esimov/pigo
#             (Pixel Intensity Comparison-based Object detector,
#             also by Endre Simo) to find face bounding boxes
#             and inflate their energy to PROTECT them from
#             seam removal; --angle controls face rotation
#             tolerance
#           - MASK FILES via --mask + --rmask:
#               * --mask PATH      retain area (inflate energy
#                                    in masked regions)
#               * --rmask PATH     remove area (reduce energy
#                                    in masked regions; force
#                                    removal)
#           - DEBUG VISUALIZATION via --debug — render the
#             chosen seams visually on the output image with
#             --color HEX (default red) using --shape circle
#             or --shape line
#           - GIO GUI PREVIEW via --preview (default true) —
#             uses gioui.org for a real-time GUI window
#             showing the carving progress; processing runs on
#             a goroutine while Gio runs on the main OS thread
#             (required for macOS event loop semantics)
#           - PERCENTAGE MODE via --perc — interpret --width /
#             --height as percentages of original (e.g. -width
#             80 -perc → 80% of original width)
#           - SQUARE MODE via --square — automatically resize
#             to square dimensions using the smaller dimension
#           - PIPE STDIN/STDOUT — "-" for --in or --out reads /
#             writes to stdin / stdout (default both)
#           - CONCURRENT WORKERS via --conc N — number of
#             goroutines for parallel processing
#             (default runtime.NumCPU())
#           - DISINTEGRATION/IMAGING for I/O — fundamental
#             image operations (load/save/convert/transform)
#             via disintegration/imaging; seam carving algorithm
#             implemented directly in carver.go
#         Used by: photographers wanting to resize without
#         cropping or distortion, web developers preparing
#         responsive image variants without losing content,
#         computer-vision researchers studying seam carving,
#         and as a reference implementation of disintegration/
#         imaging + esimov/pigo + gioui.org + stdlib flag
#         composition in Go.
#
# Author:  Endre Simo (esimov on GitHub) — Romanian Go +
#          Python computer vision developer.  Maintains an
#          ecosystem of image-processing libraries:
#            * caire        — seam carving                        (THIS)
#            * pigo         — Pixel Intensity Comparison face detection
#            * stackblur-go — fast Gaussian blur approximation
#            * triangle     — triangulated image art
#            * pixie        — primitive shape image
#                              approximation
#            * dithergo     — image dithering
#          Released caire ~2018; current version 1.5.0;
#          active development through 2026.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/esimov/caire
#          https://github.com/esimov/caire/blob/master/cmd/caire/main.go
#          https://github.com/esimov/caire/blob/master/go.mod
# CLI:     cmd/caire/main.go — uses Go stdlib `flag` package
#          (not cobra / urfave/cli; minimal footprint).
#          Headline library: **disintegration/imaging** (the
#          new variant being documented here, expanding Axis
#          22 — Image Processing — to Go).
# Library: github.com/disintegration/imaging v1.6.2
#          ("imaging" — "Imaging is a simple image processing
#           package for Go" — Grigory Dryapak (disintegration
#           on GitHub).  Distinct from image-rs/image (R677,
#           Rust Axis 22 opener) by being:
#              1. PURE GO — disintegration/imaging is 100%
#                 pure Go; no Cgo dependencies; works on any
#                 platform Go supports without C toolchain.
#                 Distinct from h2non/bimg (libvips C bindings)
#                 + go-skia (Skia C++ bindings).  Same
#                 pure-implementation choice as image-rs/image
#                 (which is pure Rust).
#              2. STDLIB image PACKAGE WRAPPER — imaging
#                 wraps Go's stdlib `image` + `image/color`
#                 packages with higher-level operations:
#                   import "github.com/disintegration/imaging"
#                   img, err := imaging.Open("photo.jpg")
#                   if err != nil { return err }
#                   img = imaging.Resize(img, 800, 0, imaging.Lanczos)
#                   img = imaging.AdjustBrightness(img, 20)
#                   img = imaging.AdjustContrast(img, 15)
#                   img = imaging.Blur(img, 2.5)
#                   imaging.Save(img, "output.jpg", imaging.JPEGQuality(80))
#                 Stdlib `image` is low-level (pixel-by-pixel
#                 access); imaging adds practical operations
#                 missing from stdlib.
#              3. 5 RESAMPLING FILTERS — for Resize / Fill /
#                 Fit operations:
#                   * NearestNeighbor (fastest, blocky)
#                   * Box (averaging, fast)
#                   * Linear (bilinear, balanced)
#                   * MitchellNetravali (mitchell-netravali)
#                   * Lanczos (highest quality, slowest)
#                 Distinct from image-rs (4 filters:
#                 Nearest/Triangle/CatmullRom/Lanczos3) with
#                 different filter taxonomy.
#              4. ~30 BUILT-IN OPERATIONS — Resize, Fit, Fill,
#                 Thumbnail, Rotate (any angle, not just 90°
#                 multiples), Rotate90/180/270, FlipH, FlipV,
#                 Transpose, Transverse, Crop, CropAnchor (with
#                 anchor: TopLeft/Top/TopRight/Left/Center/
#                 Right/BottomLeft/Bottom/BottomRight),
#                 CropCenter, Paste (overlay), PasteCenter,
#                 Overlay (with alpha blending),
#                 AdjustBrightness, AdjustContrast,
#                 AdjustGamma, AdjustSaturation, AdjustHue,
#                 Sharpen, Blur, Sobel, Invert, Grayscale.
#              5. ANCHOR-BASED CROPPING — CropAnchor takes
#                 imaging.Anchor enum: TopLeft, Top, TopRight,
#                 Left, Center, Right, BottomLeft, Bottom,
#                 BottomRight.  Distinct from image-rs which
#                 uses (x, y, width, height) rectangle.
#              6. ARBITRARY-ANGLE ROTATION via Rotate(img,
#                 angle_degrees, fill_color) — rotates by any
#                 angle (not just 90° multiples) with background
#                 fill color for newly exposed regions.
#                 Distinct from image-rs/image (only 90/180/270
#                 in imageops; arbitrary rotation requires
#                 external crate).
#              7. JPEG QUALITY OPTION — imaging.Save(img,
#                 "out.jpg", imaging.JPEGQuality(80)).  Default
#                 85.  Distinct from image-rs/image which
#                 requires explicit JpegEncoder.encode_image().
#              8. SIMPLE API — operations chain naturally;
#                 each returns a new *image.NRGBA.  Distinct
#                 from in-place modifying APIs.
#              9. NRGBA INTERNAL FORMAT — imaging converts all
#                 input formats to image.NRGBA (non-premultiplied
#                 RGBA, 8-bit per channel) internally.  Distinct
#                 from image-rs which preserves the source
#                 format.  Simplifies operation implementations
#                 but doubles memory for grayscale sources.
#             10. GRIGORY-DRYAPAK / disintegration ECOSYSTEM
#                 PROVENANCE — Grigory Dryapak (disintegration
#                 on GitHub) is a Russian Go developer.
#                 Distinct from David Tolnay (Rust serde),
#                 Sean McArthur (Hyperium / reqwest), Sindre
#                 Sorhus (Node CLI utils), image-rs working
#                 group, Vincent Prouillet (Rust tera),
#                 Florian Schlachter (Go pongo2), Vitaly
#                 Puzrin (markdown-it / js-yaml).  Solo-
#                 maintained library since 2014.)
# License: MIT (imaging); MIT (caire)
# Status:  disintegration/imaging — 5,726+ stars on
#          disintegration/imaging, ~100M go.sum downloads
#          (TOP-100 Go library); foundational image-processing
#          library used by:
#            * caire (THIS — seam carving)
#            * fyne-io/fyne (cross-platform GUI toolkit)
#            * lucasb-eyer/go-colorful (color manipulation)
#            * micro-editor/zen-screen (terminal editor)
#            * many image-processing CLIs + thumbnail
#              generators
#            * 1500+ Go applications
#          caire — 10,468+ stars on esimov/caire; widely
#          shared on Hacker News + Twitter for impressive
#          before/after image comparisons.  THE canonical Go
#          seam-carving implementation.
#
